HOUSE BILL No. 1076
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning civil
procedure.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 34-30-37 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 37. Liability Connected With Off-Road Vehicle Use on
5 Real Property
6 Sec. 1. This chapter does not:
7 (1) apply to a relationship between an employer (as defined in
8 IC 22-3-6-1(a)) and an employee (as defined in
9 IC 22-3-6-1(b)); or
10 (2) prevent or limit the liability of an owner, a spectator, or a
11 promoter that does any of the following:
12 (A) Intentionally injures a participant.
13 (B) Commits an act or omission of gross negligence
14 concerning the safety of a participant that proximately
15 causes the participant's injury or death.
16 (C) Fails to use the degree of care that an ordinarily
17 careful and prudent person would use under the same or
2026 IN 1076—LS 6463/DI 154

2
1 similar circumstances.
2 (D) Commits other acts, errors, or omissions that:
3 (i) constitute willful or wanton misconduct, gross
4 negligence, or criminal conduct; and
5 (ii) proximately cause injury, damage, or death.
6 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "inherent risks of off-road
7 vehicle use" means the dangers or conditions that are an integral
8 part of off-road vehicle use on roads, trails, paths, or other
9 surfaces, including the following:
10 (1) Injury or death caused by:
11 (A) a change or variation in the surface that may cause a
12 participant to:
13 (i) lose the ability to steer the off-road vehicle;
14 (ii) lose the participant's balance; or
15 (iii) crash the off-road vehicle;
16 (B) a collision with an object; or
17 (C) an attack by an animal.
18 (2) Operator error, including equipment failure due to
19 operator error.
20 (3) The aggravation of an already existing injury, illness, or
21 condition because the aggravation of the already existing
22 injury, illness, or condition occurred in a remote place where
23 medical facilities are not readily available.
24 Sec. 3. As used in this chapter, "off-road vehicle" means a
25 vehicle that is:
26 (1) self-propelled; and
27 (2) designed primarily for off-road use.
28 Sec. 4. As used in this chapter, "owner" means an individual, a
29 group of individuals, a club, or a business entity (as defined in
30 IC 2-2.2-1-2), whether or not operating for profit, or an employee
31 of a business entity, that owns real property and provides to a
32 participant the use of the real property for off-road vehicle use.
33 Sec. 5. As used in this chapter, "participant" means an
34 individual who rents, leases, or uses an off-road vehicle on an
35 owner's real property whether or not a fee is paid.
36 Sec. 6. As used in this chapter, "promoter" means an individual,
37 a group of individuals, a club, or a business entity (as defined in
38 IC 2-2.2-1-2), whether or not operating for profit, or an employee
39 of a business entity, that sponsors or organizes a participant's use
40 of an owner's real property for off-road vehicle use.
41 Sec. 7. As used in this chapter, "spectator" means an individual
42 that is legally present on an owner's real property for the purpose
2026 IN 1076—LS 6463/DI 154

3
1 of watching a participant engage in off-road vehicle use.
2 Sec. 8. An owner, a spectator, and a promoter are immune from
3 civil liability arising from a claim brought by a participant or the
4 participant's personal representative concerning:
5 (1) the damage to or the loss of the participant's property; or
6 (2) the participant's injury or death;
7 that results from the inherent risks of off-road vehicle use.
